                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14460843" author="phkim" created="Sat, 5 Mar 2005 15:19:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This was fixed now in jsr-1.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460825" author="jrose" created="Mon, 7 Mar 2005 06:20:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Is there some reason a more targeted fix wasn&apos;t chosen?  Only the first line needs the #! syntax, not every line.  There could be another use for &apos;#&apos; characters to build operators in 2.0.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460921" author="hoju" created="Mon, 7 Mar 2005 23:52:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In any case, the fix seems incomplete.  I can have &apos;#&apos; as the first character now, but I can&apos;t have &apos;//&apos; (less the quotes, obviously).  I get the following error...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Exception in thread &quot;main&quot; org.nanocontainer.script.groovy.NanoContainerGroovyCompilationException: Compilation Failed &apos;parsing failed&apos;&lt;br/&gt;
unexpected token: /&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;        at org.nanocontainer.script.groovy.GroovyContainerBuilder.createGroovyScript(GroovyContainerBuilder.java:94)&lt;br/&gt;
        at org.nanocontainer.script.groovy.GroovyContainerBuilder.createContainerFromScript(GroovyContainerBuilder.java:49)&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;If I leave the first line blank or use &apos;#&apos; or &apos;/*&apos; for comments, everything works fine, but if the first non-whitespace on the line is a &apos;//&apos; comment, I get the error above.  BTW, this was using a fresh jar built from the latest CVS as of this evening.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Jake&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460720" author="phkim" created="Tue, 8 Mar 2005 11:13:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is re-opened, because some problem has been found.&lt;br/&gt;
That is, we cannot use two slashes (//) commenet line with such a fix.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460677" author="jrose" created="Wed, 9 Mar 2005 07:12:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looks like an ANTLR bug, if the expression (&quot;//&quot; | &quot;#&quot;) causes &quot;//&quot; to go unrecognized.&lt;br/&gt;
I have comitted a fuller fix, which (a) recognizes &quot;#!&quot; and (b) does so only on line 1.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460897" author="hoju" created="Sat, 12 Mar 2005 02:58:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Seems to work fine now after building from the latest source.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Jake&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460790" author="jez" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2005 05:33:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This appears to be resolved.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
